# Cursor table rendering discipline

Cursor-flavor sessions in this repo have a documented history of emitting GFM pipe tables that arrive at the HAPI renderer with cells dropped or separator rows malformed, falling back to a `<p>` of literal pipe text instead of a `<table>`. This has been observed even when the agent believed it had verified the column count before sending.

**Root cause:** the agent cannot inspect its own emitted bytes — only its intended output. Any self-verification rule like "count the pipes before sending" is unfalsifiable from the agent side. The corruption window sits between agent emission and renderer input and cannot be closed by post-hoc cell counting.

**Rule:** when emitting a tabular structure in a Cursor-flavor HAPI session, use a code-fenced ASCII table, not a GFM pipe table. Fenced content bypasses the markdown table parser entirely, so column count mismatch cannot demote the table to a paragraph.

Use this shape:

```
Column A     | Column B  | Column C
-------------|-----------|---------
row 1 cell A | row 1 B   | row 1 C
row 2 cell A | row 2 B   | row 2 C
```

Pad cells so the pipes align visually — humans can read the structure without a renderer doing the work.

Reserve GFM pipe tables (`| Col | Col |` with `|---|---|` separator) for cases where the data is two columns wide or fewer and short enough to verify by eye on a single line.

This rule applies only to Cursor sessions. Other agent flavors (Claude, Codex, OpenCode) receive guidance via their HAPI system prompts; Cursor's CLI has no equivalent surface, so the rule lives here in `.cursor/rules/`.
